prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: band 7 SN >5
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: It is for single continuum obervation setup of 98 objects (69 FDs + 29 TDs) with Fnu > 0.84 mJy at band 7 for greater than 5-sigma detection.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
The major goal of this project is to obtain SEDs and to meausre disk mass and spectral index at sub-mm/radio wavelength range.
In this science goal, we aim to detect dust continuum emission at band 7 (351 GHz as the LO). The sky represenativie frequency is selected by considering to include CO (3-2) line at 345.79 GHz to get some information of gas for free.
The flux density estimation have been made by extrapolating SEDs in IR (upto 100 micron) wavelength range, then we assume the optically thick emission of dust continuum at sum-mm/radio wavelength range, which gives beta = 0 (Fnu ~ nu^(alpha+beta)).
To meet our major goal of this proposal as well as to save observation time, we request the spatial resolution of 0.5 arcsec that mostly cover disk size (few hundreds AU in radius) in Orion A (at ~410 pc). Therefore, we adopt the estimated flux density as the peak continuum flux density per beam.
The sources in this Science Goal have the estimated flux density at the representative frequency > 0.8 mJy. To reach at least 5-sigma detection, we ask 0.16 mJy for continuum sensitivity which can be reached in 2 min on-source integration time per object. And the total time including calibrationa and overhead is about 6.7 hours for 98 objects (69 radially continuous disks and 29 transitional disks).

The major goal of this project is to obtain SEDs and to meausre disk mass and spectral index at sub-mm/radio wavelength range.
In this science goal, we aim to detect dust continuum emission at band 6 (LO at 229.2 GHz). This choice of LO reduce on-source observation time to meet a requested rms almost half of the on-source time estimated in case of setting LO at 238 GHz. Not only helping the reduction of observation time, The baseband setting with LO at 229.2 GHz is useful not only to reduce the total estimated time but also to get 13CO (2-1) line at 220.39 GHz for free.
The flux density estimation have been made by extrapolating SEDs in IR (upto 100 micron) wavelength range, then we assume the optically thick emission of dust continuum at sum-mm/radio wavelength range, which gives beta = 0 (Fnu ~ nu^(alpha+beta)).
To meet our major goal of this proposal as well as to save observation time, we request the spatial resolution of 0.5 arcsec that mostly cover disk size (few hundreds AU in radius) in Orion A (at ~410 pc). Therefore, we adopt the estimated flux density as the peak continuum flux density per beam.
The sources in this Science Goal have the estimated flux density at the representative frequency > 0.42 mJy. To reach at least 5-sigma detection, we ask 0.08 mJy for continuum sensitivity which can be reached in less than 2.5 min on-source integration time per object. And the total time including calibrationa and overhead is about 7.5 hours for 98 objects (69 radially continuous disks and 29 transitional disks)

prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: band 7 faint TDs S/N=3
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: It is for single continuum obervation setup of 12 TDs with 0.84 > Fnu > 0.42 mJy at band 7 for greater than 3-sigma detection.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
The major goal of this project is to obtain SEDs and to meausre disk mass and spectral index at sub-mm/radio wavelength range.
In this science goal, we aim to detect dust continuum emission at band 7 (351 GHz as the representative band) for 12 transitional disks which have the estimated flux density between 0.8 and 0.4 mJy. The reason to separate these sources from the brighter sources is to economize the expected total observation time by giving different senstivities and S/N requirements. The 3-sigma detection is marginal, but the rms setting for 5-sigma detection renders almost three times of the estimated observation time for the case of 3-sigma.
The basebands and LO setting is same for the scienc goal for the sources with flux density > 0.8 mJy: LO at 351 GHz.
The flux density estimation have been made by extrapolating SEDs in IR (upto 100 micron) wavelength range, then we assume the optically thick emission of dust continuum at sum-mm/radio wavelength range, which gives beta = 0 (Fnu ~ nu^(alpha+beta)).
To meet our major goal of this proposal as well as to save observation time, we request the spatial resolution of 0.5 arcsec that mostly cover disk size (few hundreds AU in radius) in Orion A (at ~410 pc). Therefore, we adopt the estimated flux density as the peak continuum flux density per beam.
The sources in this Science Goal have the estimated flux density at the representative frequency in 0.8 mJy > F_nu > 0.4 mJy. To reach at least 3-sigma detection, we ask 0.14 mJy for continuum sensitivity which can be reached in 3 min on-source integration time per object. And the total time including calibrationa and overhead is about 1.21 hours for 12 objects.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose to take dust continuum survey of 110 sources in Orion A region. During ALMA cycle 2, we plan to use only two bands (band 7 and band 6) to measure disk mass and the SED slope, alpha. This proposal is a part of big program of disk mass survey in Orion A Class II Young Stellar Objects. In cycle 2, we can scan at least ~50% of objects of the whole program in less than 20 hours. The disk masses and SED slopes of outer disk continuum will be used to test disk evolution and planet formation mechanisms with other properties we have already measured -- stellar mass, mass accretion rates, F_11.3/F_9.8, R_wall, etc. This will be the first large survey of not only radially continuous Class II disks in Orion A (but not in Trapezium) span in wide stellar and disk properties but also transitional disks in various radial structures.
